To properly implement the `FileDescriptor` class with a unique ownership model, we'll need to ensure that only one instance of `FileDescriptor` can own a given file descriptor at any time. To accomplish this, we will delete the copy constructor and copy assignment operator since these would allow for the duplication of ownership. Additionally, we will implement a move constructor and move assignment operator which will transfer the ownership from one instance to another.

Here is how you can implement the class in the `filedescriptor.cpp` file:

```cpp
#include "filedescriptor.h"
#include <unistd.h>
#include <utility> // for std::swap

namespace net {

FileDescriptor::FileDescriptor() : fd_(std::nullopt) {}

FileDescriptor::FileDescriptor(int fd) : fd_(fd) {}

FileDescriptor::~FileDescriptor() {
    if (fd_.has_value()) {
        close(fd_.value());
    }
}

FileDescriptor::FileDescriptor(FileDescriptor&& other) noexcept : fd_(std::move(other.fd_)) {
    other.fd_ = std::nullopt; // explicitly set the moved-from object to an empty state
}

FileDescriptor& FileDescriptor::operator=(FileDescriptor&& other) noexcept {
    if (this != &other) {
        if (fd_.has_value()) { // Make sure to close any existing file descriptor
            close(fd_.value());
        }
        fd_ = std::move(other.fd_);
        other.fd_ = std::nullopt; // explicitly set the moved-from object to an empty state
    }
    return *this;
}

int FileDescriptor::unwrap() const {
    return fd_.value_or(-1);
}

// Copy constructors and copy assignment operators are not allowed
FileDescriptor::FileDescriptor(const FileDescriptor& other) = delete;
FileDescriptor& FileDescriptor::operator=(const FileDescriptor& other) = delete;

} // namespace net

```

To implement the copy constructor and the copy assignment operator as deleted, you can specify them as `delete`d in your `.cpp` file as shown above. Another way is to delete them directly in the header file, which often is more expressive and clear, since it will show directly in the class definition that these operations are not allowed.

Keep in mind that the close() function needs to be protected with a check to ensure that the file descriptor is valid (not -1) and that the file descriptor in the class is reset after being closed or moved from, to prevent double-closing issues or use-after-free bugs. In the example above this is done via `std::optional` and its `has_value()` method, and by explicitly setting the `other.fd_` to `std::nullopt` after moving it. If there is ever an attempt to use `fd_` after the object is moved from, `unwrap()` will safely return -1, which is indicative of an invalid file descriptor on Linux systems.

