The error is due to an improper cast from `char*` to `in_addr`. Instead of performing a `reinterpret_cast`, we should use `memcpy` to copy the bytes from `host->h_addr` to our `in_addr` structure. Here's the corrected section that handles the DNS resolution and copying:

```cpp
Connection Socket::connect(const std::string& destination, uint16_t port) {
    sockaddr_in addr = {};
    addr.sin_family = AF_INET;
    addr.sin_port = htons(port);

    if (destination == "localhost") {
        addr.sin_addr.s_addr = htonl(INADDR_LOOPBACK);
    } else {
        if (inet_pton(AF_INET, destination.c_str(), &addr.sin_addr) <= 0) {
            struct hostent* host = gethostbyname(destination.c_str());
            if (!host || host->h_length == 0) {
                throw std::runtime_error("DNS resolution failed");
            }
            std::memcpy(&addr.sin_addr, host->h_addr_list[0], host->h_length);
        }
    }

    if (::connect(fd_.unwrap(), (struct sockaddr *)&addr, sizeof(addr)) == -1) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Connection failed");
    }

    return Connection(FileDescriptor(fd_.unwrap()));
}
```

This corrected implementation uses `memcpy` to safely copy the IP address (which is in network byte order) from the `hostent` structure into the `sockaddr_in` structure's `sin_addr` field without violating strict aliasing rules. Remember that `gethostbyname` is deprecated and not thread-safe; you might want to use `getaddrinfo` in the real-world code, which also supports IPv6.

