Let's take a closer look at the `Socket::connect` method:

```cpp
Connection Socket::connect(std::string destination, uint16_t port) {
    // ... (connection setup omitted for brevity)

    if (::connect(fd_.unwrap(), reinterpret_cast<struct sockaddr*>(&addr), sizeof(addr)) == -1) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Connection failed");
    }

    // This line transfers ownership of the socket's file descriptor to the Connection object.
    return Connection(FileDescriptor(fd_.unwrap()));
}
```

The issue here is that the `connect` function transfers ownership of the client's socket file descriptor to the resulting `Connection` object. This means that when the `Connection` object goes out of scope, it will close the file descriptor that was originally "owned" by the `Socket` (i.e., `socket.fd()`).

The fix is to ensure that when `Socket::connect` is called, it duplicates the file descriptor so that `Socket` retains ownership of its original file descriptor, and the new `Connection` is given a new one. For this, we can use the `dup` system call which will create a new file descriptor referring to the same open file description as the original one. Here's the corrected implementation:

```cpp
Connection Socket::connect(std::string destination, uint16_t port) {
    // ... (connection setup omitted for brevity)

    if (::connect(fd_.unwrap(), reinterpret_cast<struct sockaddr*>(&addr), sizeof(addr)) == -1) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Connection failed");
    }

    // Duplicate the file descriptor before creating the Connection object
    int new_fd = ::dup(fd_.unwrap());
    if (new_fd == -1) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to duplicate file descriptor");
    }

    return Connection(FileDescriptor(new_fd));
}
```

